addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Galois theory combines everything we've studied so far in abstract algebra: we have fields which are super nice rings (relying on everything discussed in the <fr:link
type="local"
href="iaa-0008.xml"
addr="iaa-0008"
title="Traditional Introduction to Rings">Traditional Introduction to Rings</fr:link>) and we may view some fields as vector spaces over another (relying on everything discussed in the <fr:link
type="local"
href="iaa-0009.xml"
addr="iaa-0009"
title="Traditional Introduction to Modules">Traditional Introduction to Modules</fr:link>).</fr:p><fr:p>We can translate "roots of a polynomial" into "field extensions", and then study the symmetries of field extensions leaving the base field invariant. This relies on everything we learned in the <fr:link
type="local"
href="iaa-0001.xml"
addr="iaa-0001"
title="Traditional Introduction to Groups">Traditional Introduction to Groups</fr:link>.</fr:p><fr:p>In other words, Galois theory combines everything we have learned into a single application (i.e., solving polynomials over fields). <fr:link
type="local"
href="emmy-noether.xml"
addr="emmy-noether"
title="Emmy Noether">Emmy Noether</fr:link> is responsible for this presentation of material, but <fr:link
type="local"
href="bartel-van-der-waerden.xml"
addr="bartel-van-der-waerden"
title="Bartel L. van der Waerden">Bartel L. van der Waerden</fr:link> usually gets credit for it since it's basically the content of <fr:link
type="local"
href="van-der-waerden-1949-modern1.xml"
addr="van-der-waerden-1949-modern1"
title="Modern Algebra, Vol. I">Modern Algebra, Vol. I</fr:link>...but people don't realize that Emmy Noether is the person who wrote the outline and highlighted the importance of this structure to the presentation of material.</fr:p><fr:p>Before I forget, these are mostly based on my notes and the notes of Zavosh Amir-Khosravi (who used them for Caltech's Math 5C course for Spring quarter 2018).</fr:p><fr:p>There are plenty of good lecture notes on Galois theory nowadays. An incomplete selection which I found useful:</fr:p><fr:ul><fr:li>Tom Leinster's "<fr:link
type="local"
href="leinster-2024-galois.xml"
addr="leinster-2024-galois"
title="Galois Theory">Galois Theory</fr:link>" <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.07499">arXiv:2408.07499</fr:link> (152 pages)</fr:li>
<fr:li>Brent Everitt's "Galois Theory - a first course" <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1804.04657">arXiv:1804.04657</fr:link> (94 pages)</fr:li></fr:ul></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
